ent in Palestine's modern history. Making these never-before-published reflections available in translation, Kimberly Katz also provides illuminating context for Sāmī's words, laying out biographical details of Sāmī, who kept his diary private for close to sixty years. One of a limited number of Palestinian diaries available to English-language readers, the diary of Sāmī ‘Amr bridges significant chasms in our understanding of Middle Eastern, and particularly Palestinian, history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aPalestinian ArabsvDiaries. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Palestinian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zJerusalem. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zPalestine. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aKatz, Kimberly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTamari, Salim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTamari, Salim.1 aʿAmr, Sāmī, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799226423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799226/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK